ement: the UPCN identifies as predominantly Peronist, disciplined, and supportive of incumbent government, while the ATE prides itself on its democratic, horizontal approach and relative autonomy from the electoral process. Sian Lazar examines how activists in both unions create themselves as particular kinds of militants and forms of political community. The Social Life of Politics places the lived experience of political activism into historical relief and shows how ethics and family values deeply inform the process by which political actors are formed, understood, and joined together through collectivism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aLabor movementzArgentina. 0aLabor unionsxPolitical activityzArgentina. 0aPolitical activistszArgentina. 0aPolitical culturezArgentina. 4aactivism. 4acollective. 4acontainment. 4adispositions. 4aethical subjectivation. 4apolitical community. 4asocial movements. 4atrade unions. 4avalues. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311070369640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360242740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503602427423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503602427.jpg  a978-3-11-070369-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles